<!-- SECTION 2: RENDER PIPELINE -->
<section class="hidden" id="pipeline">
<h2>// Render Pipeline</h2>
<p>The GPU render pipeline transforms 3D geometry into 2D pixels through a sequence of programmable and fixed-function stages. Every frame: vertices → triangles → fragments → pixels. The programmer controls the vertex shader and fragment shader; the hardware handles rasterization, depth test, and blending.</p>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="200" id="pipelineCanvas"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-label">realtime render pipeline — animated data flow</div>
</div>
<div class="slider-row">
<label>// pipeline_speed</label>
<input id="pipeSpeedSlider" max="100" min="10" type="range" value="60"/>
<span id="pipeSpeedVal">0.60</span>
</div>
<div class="card-grid">
<div class="card"><h3>Vertex Shader</h3><p>Transforms each vertex position from object space through world → view → clip space. Runs once per vertex on the GPU. Outputs gl_Position and varyings.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>Rasterization</h3><p>Fixed-function hardware converts triangles into fragments (potential pixels). Interpolates vertex attributes (UVs, normals) across the triangle surface.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>Fragment Shader</h3><p>Computes final pixel color. Texture sampling, lighting calculations, procedural effects. Runs once per fragment — the bottleneck for complex scenes.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>Output Merge</h3><p>Depth test rejects occluded fragments. Alpha blending composites transparency. Stencil operations mask regions. Final pixel written to framebuffer.</p></div>
</div>
</section>
<div class="divider"></div>
<!-- SECTION 3: GPU ARCHITECTURE -->
<section class="hidden" id="gpu">
<h2>// GPU Architecture</h2>
<p>Modern GPUs are massively parallel processors with thousands of shader cores executing the same program on different data (SIMD). NVIDIA Ampere/Ada, AMD RDNA3, and Apple M-series GPUs differ in microarchitecture but share the same shader execution model.</p>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="240" id="gpuCanvas"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-label">GPU compute unit visualization</div>
</div>
<div class="slider-row">
<label>// compute_units</label>
<input id="cuSlider" max="128" min="8" type="range" value="64"/>
<span id="cuVal">64</span>
</div>
<div class="slider-row">
<label>// occupancy</label>
<input id="occSlider" max="100" min="10" type="range" value="75"/>
<span id="occVal">75%</span>
</div>
<div class="card-grid">
<div class="card"><h3>Shader Cores (ALUs)</h3><p>Each SM (NVIDIA) or CU (AMD) contains 64–128 shader processors. RTX 4090: 16,384 CUDA cores across 128 SMs. Peak: 82.6 TFLOPS FP32.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>VRAM &amp; Bandwidth</h3><p>GPU memory bandwidth is the primary bottleneck for texture-heavy scenes. RTX 4090: 1008 GB/s. Texture caches (L1/L2) reduce bandwidth pressure.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>Warp / Wavefront</h3><p>32 threads (NVIDIA warp) or 64 threads (AMD wavefront) execute in lockstep. Divergent branching serializes execution — minimize branching in shaders.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>Ray Tracing Cores</h3><p>Dedicated BVH traversal hardware (RTX). Handles triangle-ray intersection at hardware speed. Enables real-time reflections, shadows, and GI.</p></div>
</div>
</section>
<div class="divider"></div>
<!-- SECTION 4: FRAME TIMING -->
<section class="hidden" id="timing">
<h2>// Frame Timing</h2>
<p>Real-time graphics demands consistent frame delivery. At 60fps, each frame has 16.67ms budget. CPU submits draw calls; GPU executes them in parallel. GPU timing tools (NVIDIA NSight, RenderDoc) reveal which passes consume the most time.</p>
<div class="canvas-wrap">
<canvas height="200" id="timingCanvas"></canvas>
<div class="canvas-label">frame timeline — GPU pass breakdown</div>
</div>
<div class="slider-row">
<label>// target_fps</label>
<input id="fpsSlider" max="144" min="24" type="range" value="60"/>
<span id="fpsVal">60 fps</span>
</div>
<div class="slider-row">
<label>// scene_complexity</label>
<input id="complexSlider" max="100" min="10" type="range" value="50"/>
<span id="complexVal">50%</span>
</div>
<div class="card-grid">
<div class="card"><h3>CPU Frame Time</h3><p>Game logic, animation, physics, draw call submission. CPU sends command buffer to GPU. Goal: ≤8ms for 60fps split between CPU and GPU.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>GPU Frame Time</h3><p>Shadow map rendering, G-buffer pass, lighting pass, post-processing. GPU stalls occur when VRAM bandwidth or shader ALU are saturated.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>V-Sync &amp; Tearing</h3><p>V-Sync locks frame presentation to display refresh, preventing tearing at cost of latency. NVIDIA G-Sync / AMD FreeSync enable variable refresh rate.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h3>GPU-Driven Rendering</h3><p>Multi-Draw Indirect (MDI) lets GPU fetch draw calls from VRAM buffer, reducing CPU-GPU synchronization. Enables 10–100× draw call count increase.</p></div>
</div>
</section>
<div class="divider"></div>
<!-- SECTION 5: LIGHTING SIMULATION -->
<section class="hidden" id="lighting">
<h2>// Lighting Systems</h2>
<p>Real-time lighting has evolved from per-vertex Gouraud shading to physically-based deferred rendering with ray-traced global illumination. Each technique trades accuracy for performance within the frame budget.</p>
